dataCollectionDates.value: Data collection will start on 1. March 2020 and will end on 15. April 2020. The giving in of the bachelor thesis is the 15. June 2020.

question2a.value: It is a within-subjects study design. The independent variables are grandiose narcissism and vulnerable narcissism. These two variables are probably not orthogonal because both of them are dimensions of the trait narcissism.

question2b.value: Grandiose narcissism, vulnerable narcissism, self-esteem, positive agency, negative agency and self-compassion. Dependent variables for the mediation are self-esteem and self-compassion.

question10b.value:
It will be an online-questionnaire study. Data is collected from subjects that are not randomly assigned to a treatment. No blinding is involved in this study. The following traits will be measured with the following questionnaires:
1. Grandiose narcissism will be measured with the German Version of the Narcissistic Personality Inventory with 40 forced-coice items (Raskin & Terry, 1988).
2. Vulnerable narcissism will be measured with the German Version of the Narcissistic Inventory with 36 items (Rohmann, Neumann, Herner, & Bierhoff, 2012).
3. Self-esteem will be measured with the German Version of the Rosenberg-Self-Esteem-Scale with a four-point response scale  (Collani & Herzberg, 2003).
4. Positive agency will be measured with the German Version of the Extended Personal Attributes Questionnaire (Runge et al., 1981) with a five-point response scale but without the item "competitive".
5. Negative Agency will be measured with the German Version of the Extended Personal Attributes Questionnaire (Runge et al., 1981) with a five-point response scale.
6. Self-compassion will be measured with the German Version of the Self-Compassion Scale (Hupfeld & Ruffieux, 2011).

7. Life satisfaction will be measured with the German Version of the Satisfaction with Life Scale (Glaesmer, Grande, Braehler, & Roth, 2011) for exploratory examinations.

These scales will be presented in a random order, so that no order effects can occur.

question4b.value: Only participants who are at least 18 years old can participate in this study.

question5b.value: Participants will be recruited among university students at Ruhr-Universität Bochum in Germany and via social platforms (Instagram, Facebook, WhatsApp). For recruitment there will be a link.  Psychology students will earn 0.5 hours for their participation as a study participant. I will create a cross-sectional online study using Qualtrics to create the questionnaire. With respect to eligibility participants must be at least 18 years old.

question6b.value:
For correlation analysis based upon .8 statistical power, with error probability of .05, and an estimated medium effect size of .3. using the G*power program, the required sample size is N = 82 (two-tailed test).

For mediation analysis I computed a Monte Carlo Power Analysis for Indirect Effects based on a statistical power of .8. The required sample size is N = 307 (Schoemann, Bolton, & Short, 2017). The results from Rohmann et al. (2019) were used to calculate the Monte Carlo Power Analysis for Indirect Effects. Grandiose narcissism and vulnerable narcissism were used as independent variables, self-esteem as the dependent variable and positive and negative agency as mediators. There are no existing results for self-compassion but it is plausible that the results are similiar like the correlations with self-esteem because self-compassion and self-esteem correlate highly positive (Hupfeld & Ruffieux, 2011).
Rohmann et al. (2019) found high correlations so the required sample size is large (N = 307). It should be mentioned that in social psychology the average correlation is r = .21 (Richard, Bond, & Stokes-Zoota, 2003). Rohmann et al. (2019) used another method. They used table 3 from Fritz and MacKinnon (2007) to determine the estimated medium-sized effects for mediation analysis, the sample size was 71. Ergo there is a large range.

question7b.value: The collection of the data will end on 15. April 2020. If there are enough participants before this date, I will stop the data collection earlier. This project is limited so data collection cannot go longer.

question8b.value: I will only include cases with complete data and only participants who are at least 18 years old.

question1a.value:
1a. The link between grandiose narcissism and self-esteem is mediated by positive agency. 
1b.The grandiose narcissism will negatively relate to self-esteem and this will be mediated by negative agency.
2a. The negative link between vulnerable narcissism and self-esteem will be mediated by low positive agency.
2b. The negative link between vulnerable narcissism and self-esteem will be mediated by negative agency.
3. Grandiose narcissism will negatively relate to self-compassion and this will be mediated by negative agency.
4a. The negative link between vulnerable narcissism and self-compassion will be mediated by low positive agency.
4b. The negative link between vulnerable narcissism and self-compassion will be mediated by negative agency.

question2a.value: There are no interaction effects expected.

question3a.value: There will be no manipulation because it is just a questionnaire study.

question5a.value: The first figure „Results (Rohmann et al., 2019)“ shows the results from Rohmann, Brailovskaia and Bierhoff (2019). The study depends on the Extended Agency Model in which agency connects narcissism with self-esteem  (Campbell and Foster 2007). Further research showed that grandiose narcissism and self-esteem are positively related and this is mediated by positive agency. Vulnerable narcissism and self-esteem are negatively related and this is mediated by low positive agency (Brown et al., 2016). The study wanted to focus more on vulnerable narcissism and negative agency and not only on positive agency and grandiose narcissism. I want to replicate the results of this study and to expand it by self-compassion. The mediation models for the hypothesis for self-compassion are showed in the second figure „Model for Mediation 1“ and in the third figure „Model for mediation 2“. The hypothesis also depend on the Extended Agency Model and on the results from Rohmann et al. (2019). Self-compassion and self-esteem correlate highly positive (Hupfeld & Ruffieux, 2011) so it is plausible that self-compassion correlates in the same way with positive and negative agency like self-esteem. Neff (2003) found a nonsignificant positive correlation between self-compassion and grandiose narcissism and Hupfeld and Ruffieux (2011) a small positive correlation. Neff (2003) calculated also a partial correlation between self-compassion and the NPI (that measures grandiose narcissism) controlled for the variance due to self-esteem and found a nonsignificant negative correlation with narcissism, r = - .08. Owing to the characteristics of self-compassion described by Hupfeld and Ruffieux (2011) and Neff (2003) it is plausible for me that vulnerable and grandiose narcissism do not match self-compassion. Maybe it is possible to find significant negative correlations even if there is no existing data that shows negative correlations.

attributes.title: Title length affects number of citations

q1.value: Effect of title length on number of citations

q2.value: Richard Hardy, Jefferson Brand, Emily Monroe, Jordan Wolford, Mackenzie Burris, Vivian Vue

q3.value: Citation rates are used to measure the impact of the article.  Considering that the title is one of the most important parts of a manuscript, it is imperative to evaluate the impact that the title of articles have on their citations rates.

q5.value: Meta-Analysis - A systematic review of published studies.

value: No blinding is involved in this study.

question.value: This study will be a systematic review and Meta-Analysis. Inclusion criteria include (1) title length of a manuscript, (2) number of citations referenced in a manuscript.

q10.value: Registration prior to analysis of the data

q11.value: We searched the websites Embase, Cochrane database, and pubmed to determine available evidence.  The data has not been evaluated or analyzed.

question.value: Each study will be placed into endnote and de-duplicated. We will receive full text of the studies that meet inclusion criteria. Information will then be taken from each study and inserted into an excel document. Two researchers will examine the studies and decide if they meet the inclusion criteria. Discrepancies will be resolved by a third researcher.  Quality will be assessed using the Standard Quality Assessment Criteria for Evaluating Primary Research Papers from a Variety of Fields checklist.

q13.value: Our target is to find all articles that meet our search criteria.

question.value: We will measure if title length affects the number of citations received.
A meta-analysis that combines the results of multiple scientific studies.

q21.value: We will use the standard p<.05 criteria.

q22.value: Articles that are book chapters, case reports, case series, editorials, expert opinion, letters, Meta-Analysis or systematic reviews, written in another language other than English, or the full text is not available will be excluded.
